📘 Subject: General Studies Paper I (Prelims – Polity)
🧠 Topic: High Courts in India

(Important for Prelims + connects with Judiciary structure.)

1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 What are High Courts?

High Courts are the highest judicial bodies at the state level.

📌 Mentioned in Articles 214–231

Every state has a High Court (some states share one HC).

🔵 Composition
Chief Justice
Other Judges

📌 Number of judges is decided by the President.

🔹 Appointment of Judges
Appointed by the President
Consultation with:
Chief Justice of India
Governor of the state
Chief Justice of High Court

📌 Collegium system applies here too.

🔴 Qualifications

To become a High Court judge:

Citizen of India
At least:
10 years as advocate OR
10 years judicial office
🔹 Tenure
Retires at 62 years

📌 Difference from Supreme Court (65 years).

🔹 Jurisdiction of High Court
1️⃣ Original Jurisdiction
Cases directly filed
2️⃣ Appellate Jurisdiction
Appeals from lower courts
3️⃣ Writ Jurisdiction (Article 226)
Can issue writs for:
Fundamental Rights
Other legal rights

📌 Wider than Supreme Court.

4️⃣ Supervisory Jurisdiction
Supervises lower courts
🔹 Important Points
High Court ensures justice at state level
Can issue writs even beyond Fundamental Rights
Acts as guardian of Constitution at state level
